HEADWORD: Chronology
<hw>Chro*nol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Chronologies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <?/ time +
<?/ discourse: cf. F. <ets>chronologie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The science
which treats of measuring time by regular divisions or periods, and
which assigns to events or transactions their proper dates.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If history without <qex>chronology</qex> is dark and confused,
<qex>chronology</qex> without history is dry and insipid.</q>
<rj><qau>A. Holmes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chronometer</ent>⟦br⟧
